window.DIARY_DATA = {"years": [{"year": 1978, "months": [{"month": 5, "month_name": "May", "entries": [{"index": 0, "date_display": "Friday, 19 May 1978", "date_str": "19/5/78", "text": "I spent the day 'feeling' my way through the technical problems associated with conjugating glycogen to microccal nuclease. Later in the afternoon Judy and the kids arrived from the farm and picked me up at work. Mark is nearly 9 now and has just begun to drive vehicles around the fields. He is immensely proud of this and has managed to 'casually' introduce this subject into at least one conversation I was having with my friends.", "page_ids": [1], "scan_page_ids": [1], "prediction_ids": ["P1_L1", "P1_L2", "P1_L3", "P1_L4", "P1_L5", "P1_L6", "P1_L7"]}, {"index": 1, "date_display": "Saturday, 20 May 1978", "date_str": "20/5/78", "text": "A very domestic weekend working around the house and shopping. I did go in and do a little error hunting on my RET4 programme on the computer Saturday afternoon and Sunday afternoon we went for a drive to MYPONGA to buy cheese and yoghurt. It was a breath-takingly beautiful morning so that the short drive South and back was a very pleasant experience. Our neighbours are beginning to discuss unemployment\n\nmore and more. They seem to view it as some sort of social disgrace to have an unemployed neighbour, rather left a minor sex offense or something. This curious response is slightly mingled with fear and is although still a minor phenomenon, a little unpleasant. A very domestic weekend working around the house and shopping. I did go in and do a little error hunting on my RET4 programme on the computer Saturday afternoon and Sunday morning we went for a drive to MYPONGA to buy cheese and yoghurt. It was a breath-takingly beautiful morning so that the short drive South and back was a very pleasant experience. Our neighbours are beginning to discuss unemployment more and more. They seem to view it as some sort of social disgrace to have an unemployed neighbour, rather like a minor sex offense or something. This curious response is slightly mingled with fear and is although still a minor phenomenon, a little unpleasant.", "page_ids": [2, 3], "scan_page_ids": [2], "prediction_ids": ["P2_L1", "P2_L2", "P2_L3", "P2_L4", "P2_L5", "P2_L6", "P2_L7", "P2_L8", "P2_L9", "P2_L10", "P2_L11", "P3_L1", "P3_L2", "P3_L3", "P3_L4", "P3_L5", "P3_L6", "P3_L7", "P3_L8", "P3_L9", "P3_L10", "P3_L11", "P3_L12", "P3_L13", "P3_L14", "P3_L15"]}, {"index": 2, "date_display": "Monday, 22 May 1978", "date_str": "22/5/78", "text": "This was a week of 'locust-days' That is to say, days that were very closely programmed so that time slipped away without any issue' other than that from my spectrophotometers and columns. I already have slight twinges of indigestion from poor eating habits and hassle from the computer and other terminals. The tea table conversation in biology has covered a number of points - firstly we are gloating over the fall-off in student numbers to philosophy and the apparent recovery of the sciences. Everybody seems to take a distinct pleasure in contemplating any discor Store of the philosophy dept. Secondly we have been moaning about the low quality of this years honours students. It seems to be part of a growing trend for our better students to leave us for the medical school and this is a very annoying degradation of our student body. Finally we have all been talking about the evident distress and suffering in the community as unemployment spreads in South Australia", "page_ids": [4, 5], "scan_page_ids": [3], "prediction_ids": ["P4_L1", "P4_L2", "P5_L1"]}, {"index": 3, "date_display": "Saturday, 27 May 1978", "date_str": "27/5/78", "text": "Very little of importance to report. I have mainly 'lived' at the computer terminal and at the lab bench in a desperate hurry to get as much done as possible before lectures start.", "page_ids": [5], "scan_page_ids": [4], "prediction_ids": ["P5_L2", "P5_L3", "P5_L4", "P5_L5", "P5_L6", "P5_L7", "P5_L8", "P5_L9", "P5_L10", "P5_L11", "P5_L12", "P5_L13", "P5_L14", "P5_L15"]}, {"index": 4, "date_display": "Sunday, 28 May 1978", "date_str": "28/5/78", "text": "The infrequency of these entries reflects the enjoyable predictability of my days. I have been mainly involved in a flurry of work in an attempt to get as much done as possible before lectures demand upon me. The weather is beautiful although cool so that the walk I took on the beach today (4/6/78) was a real pleasure. There have been more reports in the paper on drug drug abuse in this area (Morphetvale school this time) so it appears that this major disease of non-disciplined societies is spreading very effectively through our district. Bill Elliot (the prof of Biochem at Adelaide) believes that decadent societies are amongst the most intellectually productive ones and that we should concentrate on making our decadent phase productive rather than attempt to halt the progress of decay. However my personal life is enormously satisfying and happy so all this gloom is hard to accept at present.", "page_ids": [6], "scan_page_ids": [5], "prediction_ids": ["P6_L1", "P6_L2", "P6_L3", "P6_L4", "P6_L5", "P6_L6", "P6_L7", "P6_L8"]}]}, {"month": 6, "month_name": "June", "entries": [{"index": 5, "date_display": "Monday, 5 June 1978", "date_str": "5/6/78", "text": "Quietly grinding through lecture preps, programme writing for the DEC-10 and carrying on a preparation of conjugated microccal nuclease. I spent this evening reading on the monitor for the INTEL microproccesor I am trying to get going. I feel that I have as much work going as I can handle at the moment. I look forward to the medical sciences club tomorrow night as a quiet, restful evening (I hope). Judy is enormously happy to be back in the routine of domestic life and I must admit that I am too.", "page_ids": [7], "scan_page_ids": [6], "prediction_ids": ["P7_L1", "P7_L2", "P7_L3", "P7_L4", "P7_L5", "P7_L6"]}, {"index": 6, "date_display": "Saturday, 10 June 1978", "date_str": "10/6/78", "text": "Saturday. I spent the whole day reading about the 8080 microprocessor, Sketching the programme I will use to process the timetable results and taking a walk on the beach. In the evening we had Elizabeth & William Lawson as guests at Dinner. Liz is an old undergraduate friend of Judy's and Bill is her husband. They brought their child and our kids stayed up late playing with her. We ate, drank, discussed a little politics and a little gossip.", "page_ids": [8], "scan_page_ids": [8], "prediction_ids": ["P8_L1", "P8_L2", "P8_L3", "P8_L4", "P8_L5", "P8_L6"]}, {"index": 7, "date_display": "Sunday, 11 June 1978", "date_str": "11/6/78", "text": "Sunday – Given over, almost entirely, to writing lecture notes, finishing a re-reading of my copy of the ‘Memoirs of Hadrian’ by Marguerite Yourcenar and a walk on the beach. The memoirs of Hadrian was the translation of Grace Flick, and as before, I found it a quietly ‘moving’ book. I most certainly must return to Tivoli one day and carefully re-visit Hadrian’s villa At the moment I am enjoying some mournful but beautiful guitar music", "page_ids": [9], "scan_page_ids": [9], "prediction_ids": ["P9_L1", "P9_L2", "P9_L3", "P9_L4", "P9_L5", "P9_L6", "P9_L7"]}, {"index": 8, "date_display": "Monday, 12 June 1978", "date_str": "12/6/78", "text": "School Board meetings, computer programmes, lectures, the 8080 microprocessor. I find that cutting programme and working at the computer key board tends to make me tense and bed lempened if I keepit up for a long time. It is curiously difficult to put down and forget even when you know that you are getting tired and short tempered. I have just re- -read a pleasant, illustrated description of Pompeii and Herculaneum by Michael Grant. 'Cities of Vesuvius' I watched a 'Norman Gunston' special on TV tonight and had my usual desperate urge to turn it off so to -m sympatheticly relieve the embarrassment. However I managed to resist it and felt that once again my will triumphant! Fanfare). Tomorrow night I will do my best to watch something totally relaxing if I get the time", "page_ids": [10], "scan_page_ids": [10], "prediction_ids": ["P10_L1", "P10_L2", "P10_L3", "P10_L4", "P10_L5", "P10_L6", "P10_L7", "P10_L8", "P10_L9", "P10_L10", "P10_L11", "P10_L12"]}, {"index": 9, "date_display": "Friday, 16 June 1978", "date_str": "16/6/78", "text": "On the evening of Saturday the 17th Judy and I went to have a meal with Jenny Skinner (my assistant) and Keith Dixon (Lecturer in Developmental Biology) We ate, discussed politics, travel and looked out over the Gulf from their flat (At Glenelg). Joe Orbach and his wife were the other guests Time has passed almost unnoticed as I processed data, shopped, wrote & debug programmes and read more about the Intel 8080. My first attempt to digest\n\nchromatin with micrococcal nuclease was not very successful but I must await long counts before I can judge the expt properly.", "page_ids": [11], "scan_page_ids": [11], "prediction_ids": ["P11_L1", "P11_L2", "P11_L3", "P11_L4", "P11_L5", "P11_L6", "P11_L7", "P11_L8", "P11_L9"]}, {"index": 10, "date_display": "Wednesday, 21 June 1978", "date_str": "21/6/78", "text": "Hectic week of lectures, discussions and general school activities. Ray Watson (Judy's brother) came down today. He will be staying with relatives in Adelaide while he does some sort of wool-classing course. Last night ( Saturday the 24th) Judy and I went to Max and Helen Clark's house for a dinner. We thoroughly enjoyed ourselves and I had one of my usual long 'Social arguments with Helen.", "page_ids": [12], "scan_page_ids": [12], "prediction_ids": ["P12_L1", "P12_L2", "P12_L3", "P12_L4", "P12_L5", "P12_L6"]}, {"index": 11, "date_display": "Thursday, 29 June 1978", "date_str": "29/6/78", "text": "My Conjugated Micrococcal nuclease expts. are finally bearing fruit. I I plotted and planned all through the I laboriously worked out the results of the first experiment that worked. (ie- results with high enough counts to be interpretable.) My daily regime has fallen into a satisfying pattern. I get up at approx 7.00 AM, take a short run around the little 'reserve' nearby, have and shower, and finally have breakfast. The drive to Flinders takes approx 15 - 45 minutes and is getting noticeably slower each year. Today there was a railway strike and it took 45 minutes. It is much more efficient to drive in a little later, thus missing the crowded period. I spend the day involved in an admixture of lectures discussions and sessions at the computer terminal. A considerable amount of time is used drinking tea, eating and walking to buy lunch or to go to the bank. At the end of the day I drive home, again wasting at least 30 mins, and then get involved in transporting the children to and from their various activities. the remainder of the evening is reserved for light reading and some study. I like watching T.V but there seems to be a decreasing number of shows that interest me. I have just finished a book - 'Slave ship' by Eric Corder (a Pan paperback) This was another in the current wave of books expressing great common for the evils of the slave-trade while satisfying the average readers last for sex & violence. I, personally, quite like a little sex and violence occasionally but it is getting increasingly difficult to shock me while still retaining my interest - Old age?", "page_ids": [13], "scan_page_ids": [13], "prediction_ids": ["P13_L1", "P13_L2", "P13_L3", "P13_L4", "P13_L5", "P13_L6", "P13_L7", "P13_L8", "P13_L9", "P13_L10", "P13_L11", "P13_L12", "P13_L13", "P13_L14", "P13_L15", "P13_L16", "P13_L17", "P13_L18", "P13_L19", "P13_L20", "P13_L21", "P13_L22", "P13_L23", "P13_L24"]}]}, {"month": 7, "month_name": "July", "entries": [{"index": 12, "date_display": "Thursday, 6 July 1978", "date_str": "6/7/78", "text": "I'm afraid that I have nothing to confide to my diary because I have so little time to reflect quietly at the moment. I did watch the 'Naked Vicar' show tonight. This is a satyric-political-social comment show rather like the old 'Mavis Brampton Show'. It was bearable and relaxing but not worthy of any great comment.", "page_ids": [14], "scan_page_ids": [14], "prediction_ids": ["P14_L1", "P14_L2", "P14_L3", "P14_L4", "P14_L5"]}, {"index": 13, "date_display": "Sunday, 9 July 1978", "date_str": "9/7/78", "text": "Today I continued marking essays. My sister, Susan Calaby and her husband, Gil, came down for lunch. At the moment Ray Watson, my brother-in law (Judies brother) is staying with us and last night the three of us went to see Eric Sykes and Jimmy Edwards in their play 'Big Bad Mouse' I have the feeling that the colonial performances are more relaxed than their London performances and all-the-better for this. I thoroughly enjoyed watching such a skilled couple of old professionals.", "page_ids": [14, 15], "scan_page_ids": [14, 15], "prediction_ids": ["P14_L6", "P14_L7", "P14_L8", "P14_L9", "P14_L10", "P14_L11", "P15_L1", "P15_L2"]}, {"index": 14, "date_display": "Thursday, 13 July 1978", "date_str": "13/7/78", "text": "This week has been a little frustrating because of mechanical failures and the illness of our maintenance man. (John Ford). I am beginning to sort out a little programming on the Intel 8080 and have just begun reading a book that I purchased called - 'The promise of the coming Dark Age' by L.S. Stavrianos and so far I am not very impressed. However it is my policy to occasionally read stuff I disapprove of so I will keep at it", "page_ids": [15], "scan_page_ids": [15], "prediction_ids": ["P15_L3", "P15_L4", "P15_L5", "P15_L6", "P15_L7", "P15_L8", "P15_L9"]}, {"index": 15, "date_display": "Monday, 17 July 1978", "date_str": "17/7/78", "text": "Days drift past in a slow blur of lectures, discussions with students and fiddling with the computer Today I purchased two paper back books and spent the evening reading one of them - \"Henry Golightly’ by Geoff Pike. It was striking story obsessed with syphilis and homosexuality. I cant say that I enjoyed it but it had the feel of a story based on truth but exaggerated so as to sell well. Certainly the accounts of the training camp for boys rang unpleasantly true. I spent a few weeks at Roseworthy Agricultural College many years ago and I can clearly recognise the situations he describes. It is quite peculiar how 'universal' this patter of behaviour must be. The 'feel' of this teenage boys society with its vicious bullying weakness and cowardice of undeveloped characters and stupid blindness of the authorities is horribly familiar", "page_ids": [16], "scan_page_ids": [16], "prediction_ids": ["P16_L1", "P16_L2", "P16_L3", "P16_L4", "P16_L5", "P16_L6", "P16_L7", "P16_L8", "P16_L9", "P16_L10", "P16_L11", "P16_L12"]}, {"index": 16, "date_display": "Monday, 24 July 1978", "date_str": "24/7/78", "text": "My program of Work - manufacturing etc is getting so far behind that I am almost in despair so please forgive me 'diary' if I have little to say. Bert & Lois Watson (my parents in law) have been staying with us for a few days and we all had a very pleasant dinner last Saturday night with Tony and Cynthia Rathjen. He is a wheat breeder at the W.R.I. (Waite Inst) and has been in quite serious fear of losing his job-due to", "page_ids": [17], "scan_page_ids": [17], "prediction_ids": ["P17_L1", "P17_L2", "P17_L3", "P17_L4", "P17_L5", "P17_L6", "P17_L7"]}, {"index": 17, "date_display": "Sunday, 30 July 1978", "date_str": "30/7/78", "text": "I am beginning to slightly gain on my work load and have actually been able to sneak time to read a novel based on the life of the pharaoh, Akhenaton called \"A god against the gods.\" By Allan Drury. (Corgi publishers) I haven't finished it yet but it is extremely satisfying to read and its exploration of the effect of ugliness and beauty on a person's outlook is very good. His picture of Akhenaton standing before mirrors and the old pharaoh's comment that he had never been ‘young‘ is very believable and is very compatible with my own personal experience as a teenager. I went for a walk on the beach today with Mark and we discussed geology.", "page_ids": [18], "scan_page_ids": [18, 106], "prediction_ids": ["P18_L0", "P18_L1", "P18_L2", "P18_L3", "P18_L4", "P18_L5"]}]}, {"month": 8, "month_name": "August", "entries": [{"index": 18, "date_display": "Sunday, 13 August 1978", "date_str": "13/8/78", "text": "I have finished this years seminar-tutorial for the perspectives in Biology course. It was given about & times to groups of approx 1 dozen I concentrated on the great cultural gap betwarm the arts & the sciences I discussed how the literate manipulate the public flow of ideas to and their ideology or set of values and have science and scientists are made the scape goats for the Sungles and kind of ideologies I now have a little space time but his is directed towards a set of cupboards in the laundry. Computing is a role relaxing and fulfilling postime. We had dinner last night, with Tony and Cynthia Ruthjen at their home in blackwood. Tony is about to release a new strain of wheat he has created called 'Wanigul' I am trying to in finish off a lot of minor experiments so to complete a paper and I hope to use the few days I have between the term-end (last friday) and the exams to get some useful work done. The last few days have been very wet so that many of the local septic tanks have flooded. I have pumped mine out over my backyard but many people cannot do this because their yard is completely flooded. Consequently they pump into the gutters and I am quite fearful of the resultant health hazard. I heard a brilliant talk by a drama critic on Sunday night radio-2 ABC. It ended near 7:00 pm and it discussed the failure of political artists to mobilize the mass of the people against Hitler in Germany during the 1930's. His name was John Willett and he presented, beautifully lucidly, a whole series of ideas and opinions that I have long held. Its very satisfying to hear a really skillful thinker present something lucidly, persuasively and obviously truthfully. Basically he was saying that the political artists only succeeded in reaching those who aggreed with them already and that they alienated the uncommitted or at least failed to convert them He pointed out that one way of making sure history repeats self is to simply copy past mistakes!", "page_ids": [19], "scan_page_ids": [19], "prediction_ids": ["P19_L1", "P19_L2", "P19_L3", "P19_L4", "P19_L5", "P19_L6", "P19_L7", "P19_L8", "P19_L9", "P19_L10", "P19_L11", "P19_L12", "P19_L13", "P19_L14", "P19_L15", "P19_L16", "P19_L17", "P19_L18", "P19_L19", "P19_L20", "P19_L21", "P19_L22", "P19_L23", "P19_L24", "P19_L25", "P19_L26", "P19_L27", "P19_L28", "P19_L29", "P19_L30", "P19_L31"]}, {"index": 19, "date_display": "Friday, 18 August 1978", "date_str": "18/8/78", "text": "Friday. I have spent this week on a series of minor jobs However the Federal 'Budget' came down this week and looks like being a major source of annoyance and discussion for weeks. I hope that the squeeze on University finances is only a passing phase but I fear that it is not. Judy is now visiting her girl friend, Liz Lawson, about once a week to help her with her chores. Liz has multiple sclerosis and is finding it difficult to cope with the disease and with having a young child. I have progressed about half way through another paper on chromatin penetration and hope to finish it in a", "page_ids": [20], "scan_page_ids": [20], "prediction_ids": ["P20_L1", "P20_L2", "P20_L3", "P20_L4", "P20_L5", "P20_L6", "P20_L7", "P20_L8", "P20_L9", "P20_L10", "P20_L11", "P20_L12"]}, {"index": 20, "date_display": "Saturday, 26 August 1978", "date_str": "26/8/78", "text": "Saturday - We are able staying on the farm at Corryton Park near lucindale. This farm belongs to Judies parents Bert and Lois Watson and I have spent a pleasurable day marking Introduction to Cell & Molecular Biology papers while taking occasional short walks into the bush. The weather is cool but sunny and I have a large open fire to sit beside while marking my papers. The children called me out to see an echidna that they found in the bush about 100 yards from the house and all the wattles are blooming so things really one very pleasant and rural. I noted that many of the ground-orchids are preparing to flower. We drove to KINGSTON to attend an amateur production of ‘Rose Marie' as Ray Watson (Judies brother) is playing in it. On the way in to Kingston we passed the car of one of the cast had hit a kangaroo at high speed smashing its headlights and radiator. We kept a close watch ourselves after this and, on the way home after the show, had a narrow escape from the same thing. A very large 'roo' crossed he road in front of us and would probably been hit if we hadn't been going more slowly and carefully than usual", "page_ids": [20, 21], "scan_page_ids": [21], "prediction_ids": ["P20_L13", "P21_L1", "P21_L2", "P21_L3", "P21_L4", "P21_L5", "P21_L6", "P21_L7", "P21_L8", "P21_L9", "P21_L10", "P21_L11", "P21_L12", "P21_L13", "P21_L14", "P21_L15", "P21_L16", "P21_L17", "P21_L18", "P21_L19"]}, {"index": 21, "date_display": "Tuesday, 29 August 1978", "date_str": "29/8/78", "text": "It has been a pleasant two days. Brilliantly clear weather most of the time with all sorts of birds singing and parrots squawking. Today I spent all the morning with Mark (my son) and Ray Watson (brother-in-law) walking sheep from Kenjuray to Corryton Park. It was an Idyllically beautiful walk with green fields, bright sunshine and small flowers everywhere. I have a horrible suspicion that days like this are going to grow more beautiful in retrospect so that by the time we are old these days of youth, health and beauty will seem painfully wonderful. I must now start marking exams again.", "page_ids": [22, 23], "scan_page_ids": [22, 23], "prediction_ids": ["P22_L1", "P22_L2", "P22_L3", "P23_L1", "P23_L2", "P23_L3", "P23_L4", "P23_L5", "P23_L6", "P23_L7"]}]}, {"month": 9, "month_name": "September", "entries": [{"index": 22, "date_display": "Sunday, 3 September 1978", "date_str": "3/9/78", "text": "Home again at Seaford. Our country idyll was rudely upset by a cold virus and I have spent the last three days sweating and sneezing. Judy is in a similar mess so life has been grey and obsessed with temperatures and naso-pharyngeal comfort. Ray Watson and the kids should arrive soon as they were going to drive home separately. The newspapers seem to be deciding that the reason we all voted for Malcolm Fraser was because we prefer a competent bastard to a soft but nice guy I have just finished reading 'Passage to Mutiny' by Alexander Kent. It was not very different to a 'Horatio Hornblower' novel except for a number of obviously contrived differences plus a slight emphasis on sexual violence I started reading 'The Voice of the Crab' by Geraldine Hall but I cant hold my interest to it and will probably not finish it.", "page_ids": [24], "scan_page_ids": [24], "prediction_ids": ["P24_L1", "P24_L2", "P24_L3", "P24_L4", "P24_L5", "P24_L6", "P24_L7", "P24_L8", "P24_L9", "P24_L10", "P24_L11", "P24_L12", "P24_L13"]}, {"index": 23, "date_display": "Thursday, 21 September 1978", "date_str": "21/9/78", "text": "My diary is becoming extremely patchy again. There hasn't been much of great consequence to report. I have read a prelude to TREASURE ISLAND called the Adventures of Ben Gunn' by R.F. Delderfield and have loaned this to John Wheldrake who is in the process of re-reading the William books (Richmal Crompton) so we are both regressing to our childhoods. I am watching very little TV and am solidly involved in the years work. Tomorrow (the 22nd I will be 39 yrs old. I still have a cough from that damned cold.", "page_ids": [25], "scan_page_ids": [25], "prediction_ids": ["P25_L1", "P25_L2", "P25_L3", "P25_L4", "P25_L5", "P25_L6", "P25_L7", "P25_L8"]}, {"index": 24, "date_display": "Monday, 25 September 1978", "date_str": "25/9/78", "text": "Over the last few weeks the political scene in China has taken my attention again. It now appears that the fallibility of Mao is becoming a respectable possibility. Russia's protests to England about potential sales of the Harrier jet to China seems to indicate an increasing nervous about her neighbour. I have been engaged in marking student projects and this is a thankless task. I do not feel God-like enough to be able to judge human being's ability with the confidence necessary for a good hatchet man. I feel our students are overworked and demoralised by the employment situation. It is this not surprising that their performatures are often bad. This demoralisation is now becoming very apparent. The students are listless and seem incapable of giving the occasional intellectual sprint! ie. They does to fulfil the minimum requirements for a course without producing that occasional spent of effort on some aspect of the course that strongly interested them personally.", "page_ids": [37], "scan_page_ids": [37], "prediction_ids": ["P37_L1", "P37_L2", "P37_L3", "P37_L4", "P37_L5", "P37_L6", "P37_L7", "P37_L8", "P37_L9", "P37_L10", "P37_L11", "P37_L12", "P37_L13", "P37_L14", "P37_L15", "P37_L16"]}]}, {"month": 10, "month_name": "October", "entries": [{"index": 25, "date_display": "Tuesday, 3 October 1978", "date_str": "3/10/78", "text": "I still have a cough from that damned cold. My And my health have dominated my thoughts for the last few weeks", "page_ids": [26], "scan_page_ids": [26], "prediction_ids": ["P26_L1", "P26_L2"]}, {"index": 26, "date_display": "Tuesday, 17 October 1978", "date_str": "17/10/78", "text": "The cough has been absent for about two days now Over the last week’ have been watching 'Against the Wind' on channel 7 (Television). It is a semi-true? story about one Irish girls conviction, deportation to Australia, and life in Australia. I have quietly enjoyed it and its Progressive pro-little-man message is persuasively put without excessive preaching on the appearance of lying (at least obviously). The 'message' is not unpalatable and it is a welcome change from the near-propaganda we get from some of our unskilled 'ideologically-committed' media people. The Ananda Marg religion is much in the news at the moment and I hope that this rather repulsive sect is not the new religion that our tired civilization appears to be waiting for. The new religion, whatever it is, is going to have to avoid making any factual statements about its God's actions or Scientific Research is going to debunk it. Thus any new religion to be viable, is going to have to be very very mysterious and confine its statements to very deep statement ( ie-statements that are ambiguous, uninterpretable, but impressive!) It is worth noting that our mixing companies are sponsoring Against the Wind'. This seems to me to be incredibly shrewd because its audience will tend to have a large proportion of the mining companies national political opponents. Thus they one, wheels, pitching their message at the people who are attracted to the opposite type of message. I cant help thinking that this is remarkably shrewd thinking on their part-", "page_ids": [27, 28], "scan_page_ids": [27, 28], "prediction_ids": ["P27_L1", "P27_L2", "P27_L3", "P27_L4", "P28_L1", "P28_L2", "P28_L3", "P28_L4", "P28_L5", "P28_L6", "P28_L7", "P28_L8", "P28_L9", "P28_L10", "P28_L11", "P28_L12", "P28_L13", "P28_L14", "P28_L15", "P28_L16", "P28_L17", "P28_L18", "P28_L19", "P28_L20", "P28_L21"]}, {"index": 27, "date_display": "Saturday, 21 October 1978", "date_str": "21/10/78", "text": "Went for walk on beach today. I am healthy and the weather is beautiful - Murray. I am going to drop by the lab to finish off a counting men and to stain a student's gel. (polyacrylamide electrophoresis). After this I am taking the family to Susan's house and then Judy and I are going to Anne (Tonkin's) Wheldrake's house for her birthday party. The party will be held at her father's house. He is the present, leader of the State Liberal party, the opposition", "page_ids": [29], "scan_page_ids": [29], "prediction_ids": ["P29_L1", "P29_L2", "P29_L3", "P29_L4", "P29_L5", "P29_L6", "P29_L7"]}, {"index": 28, "date_display": "Sunday, 22 October 1978", "date_str": "22/10/78", "text": "Had a very pleasant evening at the Tonkins. Lots of good talk spiced with political gossip from old man Tonkin. I asked him when Malcolm Fraser was going to put on his economic Santa Claus act and Tonkin thought it would be about February next year. It appears that the Liberal leaders are plotting against Joh Bjelke-Petersen and hope to unthrone him in the near future on I wonder. The State premier’ wife (Adele Koh is in the terminal stages of an extremely malignant tumour and is not expected to last the week &side stayed at my sister's house overnight at West Lakes and at about 1000 AM many of the small polychasts that live in the mud were breeding. They were swimming at the water's surface with mildy masses of gametes floating out behind them and the small dream were actively feeding on them.", "page_ids": [30, 31], "scan_page_ids": [30, 31], "prediction_ids": ["P30_L1", "P30_L2", "P30_L3", "P30_L4", "P30_L5", "P30_L6", "P31_L1", "P31_L2", "P31_L3", "P31_L4", "P31_L5", "P31_L6", "P31_L7", "P31_L8", "P31_L9"]}, {"index": 29, "date_display": "Saturday, 28 October 1978", "date_str": "28/10/78", "text": "Adele Koh died last week, as expected, and now I hope State politics can revert to normalcy. The chief demonstrations got me a batch of sea-urchins from Port Stanvac and I hope to check them for usual ripenses soon. Tonight we are having Dinner at our house with John Wheldrake, Anne Wheldrake, David Catcheside and Pam Catcheside. Dean Hessch rang me today. He is holidaying in Adelaide and working with the CSIRO in Melbourne. He and Masylin live at Bacchus Marsh which seems a horribly long way to commute to work. I have asked him to give a seminar next Tuesday morning on his hair week He is culturing hair follicle in-vitro and studying development.", "page_ids": [32], "scan_page_ids": [32], "prediction_ids": ["P32_L1", "P32_L2", "P32_L3", "P32_L4", "P32_L5", "P32_L6", "P32_L7", "P32_L8", "P32_L9", "P32_L10", "P32_L11"]}, {"index": 30, "date_display": "Sunday, 29 October 1978", "date_str": "29/10/78", "text": "Noted small sore on Marks head. This evenings news stated that the Chinese govt has denounced Mao's 'little red book'. I am now beginning to wonder where this ideological purge is going to end. All our old blocks are in complete disarray - thank heavens!", "page_ids": [33], "scan_page_ids": [33], "prediction_ids": ["P33_L1", "P33_L2", "P33_L3", "P33_L4"]}]}, {"month": 11, "month_name": "November", "entries": [{"index": 31, "date_display": "Saturday, 11 November 1978", "date_str": "11/11/78", "text": "Last night I attended the 'Medical Sciences Club' with Judy and we heard two speakers talk on Medicine and the Law. One of the speakers was a psychologist who advocated no serious penalty for murders of the domestic type at least. I suspect that at least partly, he was being irresponsibly provocative merely for the sake of an effect. However there was a young Lawyer-Marxist I am acquainted with who seemed to greatly favour the idea I had a long discussion afterwards in an attempt defeat his naivete Tonight I watched a 'Four Corners' documentary on T.V. That discussed the relationship between the National Front and plain Nealser. I felt that they made a convincing case for the National Front being a Nazi front made palatable for the English (and the Australians?) I have long formed that our lefts stupid habit of labelling able their opposition, NAZI, or FASCSI will eventually cost us clearly. If these real nazi funds begun to appear their accusations of NAZI and FASUIT are going to sound like the small boy who 'cried Wolfe'. I have no desire to be bungled into a great Mittlerian disaster by our Lefties efforts to gouge out a little more forces. We have had beautiful weather this week, at least by Cambridge standards! I have decided to apply for a readership next year and I suspect my chances of success are rather low. My lab work seers to be going well and I am quite optimistic at the present", "page_ids": [34, 35], "scan_page_ids": [34, 35], "prediction_ids": ["P34_L1", "P34_L2", "P34_L3", "P34_L4", "P34_L5", "P34_L6", "P34_L7", "P34_L8", "P34_L9", "P34_L10", "P34_L11", "P35_L1", "P35_L2", "P35_L3", "P35_L4", "P35_L5", "P35_L6", "P35_L7", "P35_L8", "P35_L9", "P35_L10", "P35_L11", "P35_L12", "P35_L13"]}, {"index": 32, "date_display": "Sunday, 19 November 1978", "date_str": "19/11/78", "text": "This has been a quietly productive few days. I have managed to get ahead of my work and have browsed through - The anecdota or Secret history' by procopius. However, I'm afraid I enjoy my history digested into historical novels. The secret history was a rather boring attack on the emperor Justinian, his wife Theodora and their court. Slightly more interesting was 'The Meditations' of Marcus Aurelius Antoninus. However I am not a great admirer of this emperor. I am horribly afraid that he was not a hypocrite and I can now understand why his Son turned towards all the follies his father rejected. It must have seemed rather like choosing life instead of a slow, philosophy-induced, progressive catatonia.\n\nIf Senecca was anything like Marcus Aurelius I can understand why Nero went off the rails. I would have loved to have had a long talk with Marcus but I am just going to refuse to accept his outlook. (an irrational decision or an arbitrary rejection of his set of values if you like) I am going to adopt ‘Carmen Jones motto of living until I die and damn philosophers! I have just written a letter to Ted and Muriel Wheldrake in Yorkshire and I am going to send a note to over friends the McEwens in London", "page_ids": [36], "scan_page_ids": [36], "prediction_ids": ["P36_L1", "P36_L2", "P36_L3", "P36_L4", "P36_L5", "P36_L6", "P36_L7", "P36_L8", "P36_L9", "P36_L10", "P36_L11", "P36_L12", "P36_L13", "P36_L14", "P36_L15", "P36_L16", "P36_L17", "P36_L18", "P36_L19", "P36_L20", "P36_L21"]}, {"index": 33, "date_display": "Tuesday, 28 November 1978", "date_str": "28/11/78", "text": "My experimentation is getting quite interesting at the moment. I am attempting to identify the 110-150 A holes with proteases conjugated to glycogen. The tea-room conversation of the last few days has concentrated on the political developments in China. It seems almost as if there is another 'Prague Spring' developing I have just finished a paper-back about a Brothel in Berlin run by the Nazis as an information gathering centre. It claims to be true and has a reasonably convincing discussion of its sources at the back of the book. It is called 'Madam Kitty' and its author is Peter Norden. Published by 'Coronet' The end-of-the-year assessment", "page_ids": [38], "scan_page_ids": [38], "prediction_ids": ["P38_L1", "P38_L2", "P38_L3", "P38_L4", "P38_L5", "P38_L6", "P38_L7", "P38_L8", "P38_L9", "P38_L10"]}]}, {"month": 12, "month_name": "December", "entries": [{"index": 34, "date_display": "Tuesday, 12 December 1978", "date_str": "12/12/78", "text": "'circus' is nearly ended now although I am still reading one knows thesis. I have also been quietly re-reading some of my old books on human history and World War I. A pair of Murray Magpies have been nesting in over front garden and I have been watching the progression of their family through my study window. Today the chicks finally flew out of the nest. Two fine healthy looking little birds that looked very important in their new black and white plumage. I have just finished", "page_ids": [39], "scan_page_ids": [39], "prediction_ids": ["P39_L1", "P39_L2", "P39_L3", "P39_L4", "P39_L5", "P39_L6", "P39_L7", "P39_L8", "P39_L9", "P39_L10", "P39_L11"]}]}]}, {"year": 1979, "months": [{"month": 2, "month_name": "February", "entries": [{"index": 35, "date_display": "Monday, 5 February 1979", "date_str": "5/2/79", "text": "I am slowly getting used to the idea of becoming a maintenance man for much of my time. I am cutting out a piece of concrete over a pipe outlet by a tap-drilling. It is slow & tedious work. We have had blocked drains and a burst water pipe in the last few days and I am getting 'frazzled' The premier, Don Dunstan is back in S.Aust and he still nominally has an anti uranium stance. I will be interested to see what happens in the near future because the gossip I hear (from John Wheldrake and he gets it from Tonkin, the leader of the opposition) suggests that we are going to lose both the petrochemical plant and Roxby downs and the enrichment plant. I have just finished Seneca's 'letters from a Stoic' selected and translated by Robin Campbell. Jenny is back and work-proper has begun again. Today we a trypsin series in which conjugated trypsin was used to attack H3-Lysine labelled nuclei from rat liver nuclei. In a few days time we will do a penetratogram on Boar sperm heads Louis Herlands has been continuing to dive in local waters such as Horseshoe reef at Christies Beach, and although he is finding many echinoderms they have all shed their gamets This is presumably due to the warm water that must have been coming down the Gulf the last few weeks. Louis is making many personal contacts in the diving clubs and these are far more useful to him than our formal collection facilities I am reading 'A sense of the future' a collection of essays by I.Buenowski. Judy purchased it for me and it has been a damned good read so far. I have even got a useful idea for the lecture I am going to give to the high school teachers. I am going to contrast old biology characterized by the degreena of the always-collecter gene and the 'one protein'one gene' dogma that reached its height with the Jacob- Monod model with the 'New Molecular Biology'. A sort of Newton -> Einstein drama", "page_ids": [40, 41], "scan_page_ids": [40], "prediction_ids": ["P40_L1", "P40_L2", "P40_L3", "P40_L4", "P40_L5", "P40_L6", "P40_L7", "P40_L8", "P40_L9", "P40_L10", "P40_L11", "P40_L12", "P40_L13", "P40_L14", "P40_L15", "P41_L1", "P41_L2", "P41_L3", "P41_L4", "P41_L5", "P41_L6", "P41_L7", "P41_L8", "P41_L9", "P41_L10", "P41_L11", "P41_L12", "P41_L13", "P41_L14", "P41_L15", "P41_L16", "P41_L17", "P41_L18", "P41_L19"]}, {"index": 36, "date_display": "Tuesday, 20 February 1979", "date_str": "20/2/79", "text": "The events between China and Vietnam, and now Russia, have dominated the last few-days. While I was travelling to Flinders by bus a couple of mornings ago I heard a young man bewailing the fact that a war might kill him before 'he had a chance to live'. I hope his fears are grossly exaggerated Don Dunstan has resigned as state premier and politics within South Australia are clearly beginning to move I have been in charge of the preparation for a Biology Summer school for high school teachers over the last month or so and it will take place on the 22nd and 23rd of this month Over the last two days I have taken a couple of days of my annual leave and given my car a 'top-end' overhaul. This involves removal of the cylinder-head, cleaning it, having it re-surfaced and replacing it as well as a number of minor chores like valve grinds I'm afraid that i gave me a rather sore back from leaning over the cylinder block all the time Today has been hot again and I am not looking forward to my irregular evening (or morning) jog. Its bad enough fighting off the neighbours dogs without sweltering in the heat at the same time", "page_ids": [42], "scan_page_ids": [42], "prediction_ids": ["P42_L1", "P42_L2", "P42_L3", "P42_L4", "P42_L5", "P42_L6", "P42_L7", "P42_L8", "P42_L9", "P42_L10", "P42_L11", "P42_L12", "P42_L13", "P42_L14", "P42_L15", "P42_L16", "P42_L17", "P42_L18", "P42_L19", "P42_L20"]}, {"index": 37, "date_display": "Friday, 23 February 1979", "date_str": "23/2/79", "text": "I am still reading J. Bronowski's essays, collected together under the title 'A sense of the future' I am reading them slowly and thoroughly enjoying them. The summer school is over and appears to be a big success however my car is still overheating and I will have to get a new radiator to my triumph is a little boiled It must be about for 10 years ago now that I decided, clearly and consciously to make the search for truth the 'absolute-value' of my mental processes. I can remember the very well ; it was not a very striking setting for such a crystallization of a long period of thought but it was still memorable to me. It was on the road from Kingston to Meningie near a large granite outcrop not for from King Kingston. I was driving my family home from a holiday on the farm.", "page_ids": [43], "scan_page_ids": [43], "prediction_ids": ["P43_L1", "P43_L2", "P43_L3", "P43_L4", "P43_L5", "P43_L6", "P43_L7", "P43_L8", "P43_L9", "P43_L10", "P43_L11", "P43_L12", "P43_L13"]}, {"index": 38, "date_display": "Sunday, 25 February 1979", "date_str": "25/2/79", "text": "We drove up to Mylor today and had a barbecue lunch with Bill Elliot, Daphne Elliot, Hilda Burton and Ken Burton. Ken Burton is the author of the paper on the 'Burton' method of DNA estimation. After lunch we all took a walk through the bush around the Elliots shack. We discussed many minor things and I raised two of my hobby heroes. I proposed an alteration of Western man’s diet to the consumption of sweets before a meal not afterwards and also suggested that aluminium or nine impunity in it might compete with the chromium compounds that are thought to be necessary for the binding site of Insulin. We discussed these subjects at some length. This evening I watched one of the 'Carry On' films. It was about union trouble in a factory and was very 'Jolly' with a happy ending. I'm afraid that reality appears some what different", "page_ids": [44], "scan_page_ids": [44], "prediction_ids": ["P44_L1", "P44_L2", "P44_L3", "P44_L4", "P44_L5", "P44_L6", "P44_L7", "P44_L8", "P44_L9", "P44_L10", "P44_L11", "P44_L12", "P44_L13", "P44_L14"]}]}, {"month": 3, "month_name": "March", "entries": [{"index": 39, "date_display": "Tuesday, 6 March 1979", "date_str": "6/3/79", "text": "Today the builders began to knock holes in our floors and knocked out a wall so for better or for worse our new extension is under way. It will cost about $20,000-21,000 and I will provide approximately 7,000 directly and take a loan for the remainder. As soon as it is built I will have a vested interest in 'inflation' and indexation so I will probably vote Labour again! China is pulling back out of Vietnam and I am enjoying a leasurely re-read of Gore Vidals 'Julian'", "page_ids": [45], "scan_page_ids": [45], "prediction_ids": ["P45_L1", "P45_L2", "P45_L3", "P45_L4", "P45_L5", "P45_L6", "P45_L7", "P45_L8"]}, {"index": 40, "date_display": "Thursday, 8 March 1979", "date_str": "8/3/79", "text": "Today we spent most of the day discussing course re-arrangements in an attempt to lower the average work load within the school In the afternoon I attended a seminar given by George Brownlee ( see opposite) and I thoroughly enjoyed it. Although the basic details of the discovery of ‘introns and exons' within genes is now well known it was good to be able to swap 'ill considered opinions' with La Brownlee. I remembered him from my stay in Cambridge and he remembered me. He is about medium height, squarish, regular features and has pale reddish hair. He wears glasses and has a slightly nervous manner. After the meeting I watched Mark at his gym for a while and then drove him home. Judy is out baby sitting for the club tonight", "page_ids": [46], "scan_page_ids": [46], "prediction_ids": ["P46_L1", "P46_L2", "P46_L3", "P46_L4", "P46_L5", "P46_L6", "P46_L7", "P46_L8", "P46_L9", "P46_L10", "P46_L11", "P46_L12", "P46_L13", "P46_L14"]}, {"index": 41, "date_display": "Saturday, 17 March 1979", "date_str": "17/3/79", "text": "(Saturday) I gave my first lecture of the year this week The subject was Molecular adaptions to the environment and I was particularly concerned with the DNA repair mechanisms and The various molecular strategies adopted to cope with the continual damage the DNA has to receive. Last night I attended the Southern Districts Environment group at the Port Noarlunga, United Church opposite the Port Noarlunga Institute. We discussed boat ramps, the placing of Esplanades and coastal usage. There were representatives from the coastal protection agency & The local government and a boat users group. The boat users didn't really get a fair hearing and I did feel rather 'outraged' on their behalf. They of course, merely wanted their all-weather boat ramp at all costs but the chairman of the meeting very clearly favoured the opposite view and rather saw to it that the opposite view got a better hearing While at the meeting I did find the location of the elusive O'Sullivan's beach quandong. There is apparently a stand of these trees on the coast near a house with Garden gnomes which is near Wakelin Avenue After the meeting we saw two quite good under-water films. One of these was concerned with the Port Noarlunga reef and the other was concerned with the deeper reefs. This later film was - 'Shores of Gulf St Vincent' 25 mins. Film No. 215-405 South Australian Film Corporation Both films were enjoyable and I was particularly surprised to see a few crayfish on the Port Noarlunga reef. I didn't know that they came this far North.", "page_ids": [47, 48], "scan_page_ids": [47, 48], "prediction_ids": ["P47_L1", "P47_L2", "P47_L3", "P47_L4", "P47_L5", "P47_L6", "P47_L7", "P47_L8", "P47_L9", "P47_L10", "P47_L11", "P48_L1", "P48_L2", "P48_L3", "P48_L4", "P48_L5", "P48_L6", "P48_L7", "P48_L8", "P48_L9", "P48_L10", "P48_L11", "P48_L12", "P48_L13", "P48_L14", "P48_L15", "P48_L16", "P48_L17"]}, {"index": 42, "date_display": "Saturday, 24 March 1979", "date_str": "24/3/79", "text": "Saturday. The brick work is about 2/3 COMPLETE on our extension and I have just gashed my thumb while salvaging scrap wood from the old roof supports Yesterday I attended a lecture by Gunther Stent on the subject of Morality and Science. The talk was enjoyable if not startling original. He considered the problems caused by the deep-held ‘intuitions’ we have about reality and how we probably obtain these during our early development in a dialectic between our brain and physical reality. He ended up half-praising Taoism and I attempted to discuss this with him but we failed to effectively communicate in the short period of time he had before lunch. This was a pity (I tend to believe that most Eastern mysticism is Bogswaggle - or Balony as Mr Stent put it.)", "page_ids": [49], "scan_page_ids": [49], "prediction_ids": ["P49_L1", "P49_L2", "P49_L3", "P49_L4", "P49_L5", "P49_L6", "P49_L7", "P49_L8", "P49_L9", "P49_L10", "P49_L11", "P49_L12", "P49_L13"]}, {"index": 43, "date_display": "Tuesday, 27 March 1979", "date_str": "27/3/79", "text": "(Tuesday) Last night (Monday night) I spoke at the Salisbury CAE. to a mixture of high school students and their teachers. I spoke for about so minutes and covered a number of topics. The first was the job market in the Biological sciences fields and then I did a high speed tour of recent advances in Biology entitled 'A brief survey of Modern Biology'. Approx 200 people attended and the talk was reasonably successful. Today was relatively quiet albeit disappointing. Another attempt of mine to prepare asut5 nuclei failed and poor Daphne Elliot thought she had found a new enzymic activity in her plants but hadn't on rechecking her results. Louis Herlands left Adelaide this morning to go to Tasmania via Melbourne. CENTBA - MATRIC BIOLOGY STUDENT NIGHT. did not take much liquor at all with his lunch caught for a truew day red.", "page_ids": [50, 51, 52], "scan_page_ids": [50, 51], "prediction_ids": ["P50_L1", "P50_L2", "P50_L3", "P50_L4", "P51_L1", "P51_L2", "P51_L3", "P51_L4", "P51_L5", "P51_L6", "P51_L7", "P51_L8", "P52_L1", "P52_L2"]}]}, {"month": 4, "month_name": "April", "entries": [{"index": 44, "date_display": "Tuesday, 3 April 1979", "date_str": "3/4/79", "text": "Yesterday I attended a seminar given by John B. Gurdon (F.R.S) from the M.R.C. unit at Cambridge. The title was 'Gene Control in development and differentiation of higher organisms' and it was given to a nearly full house in the Kerr Grant lect. theatre at Adelaide Uni. I enjoyed it and I think the audience did also. Today I hosted Gurdon around Flinders and eventually took him to the airport at about 5:00 pm. (Plane due to leave at 5.45'). We discussed nucleocytoplasmic relations, cavity cavities, and chromatin. He also spoke extensively to David Catcheside and Keith Dixon. We all had lunch together at the staff club and this lunch was attended by myself, Gurdon, Ted Martin, Keith Dixon and one of his honours students. Gurdon noted that he usually drank cider because they couldn't afford wine in England but he", "page_ids": [101], "scan_page_ids": [52, 101], "prediction_ids": ["P101_L1", "P101_L2", "P101_L3"]}, {"index": 45, "date_display": "Thursday, 5 April 1979", "date_str": "5/4/79", "text": "I have remembered a minor, curious incident that occurred while Gurdon was here. That day I received a letter from Aaron Klug in answer to letter I had written to him discussing a bandwagon that appears to be rolling out to begin a gallop. This is the 'super-beads' theory of chromatin structure which neither of us believe at the moment. However while Gurdon was with me I discussed this and showed him the letter. He confessed that he could hardly contact Klug due to Klug's perpetual 'busyness' and know very little of what he was doing. I noted that I had found it easier to contact him by letter from Australia than contact him personally when I was at the MRC.! Gurdon aggreed and I jokingly suggested that he should send note to Klug via Australia in future. The truck drivers have become very militant and are blocking all the main roads into the cities and there are other signs that Australian politics is hotting up. I dont quite know what the Federal government is up to but I suspect that they are making some angled approach to the union problem (note - the truck drivers are independent operators, not unionists) Today I was a party to a crime: our chief electrical technician borrowed a Steeleye-Span record from me and copied it onto one of his cassettes and in return he copied one of his Steeleye-Span records onto a cassette for me. We are both thoroughly enjoying the fruits of our copy-right infringements.", "page_ids": [53], "scan_page_ids": [53], "prediction_ids": ["P53_L1", "P53_L2", "P53_L3", "P53_L4", "P53_L5", "P53_L6", "P53_L7", "P53_L8", "P53_L9", "P53_L10", "P53_L11", "P53_L12", "P53_L13", "P53_L14", "P53_L15", "P53_L16", "P53_L17", "P53_L18", "P53_L19", "P53_L20", "P53_L21", "P53_L22"]}, {"index": 46, "date_display": "Sunday, 8 April 1979", "date_str": "8/4/79", "text": "On Friday (the 6th) Judy and I attended the 49th meeting of the medical sciences club and enjoyed a symposium on arthritis. Yesterday, Saturday, I sorted the waste wood from the builders demolition of our old roof and carefully stacked the good wood in my car shed I have just finished reading the latest Flashman novel by George MacDonald Fraser called Flashman's Lady. I thoroughly enjoyed it and it is now going the rounds of the department I spent most of today writing lecture notes on Genetics for perspectives people & but at about 5,00 pm we all went into town to See two Marx brothers films ‘Room Service’ and ‘A night in Casablanca'. We all (Judy, Mark, Laura, Kirsty and myself) roared laughing from the beginning to the end of both films. I must now go for my short jog", "page_ids": [54, 55], "scan_page_ids": [54, 55], "prediction_ids": ["P54_L1", "P54_L2", "P54_L3", "P54_L4", "P54_L5", "P54_L6", "P54_L7", "P54_L8", "P54_L9", "P54_L10", "P54_L11", "P55_L1", "P55_L2", "P55_L3", "P55_L4"]}, {"index": 47, "date_display": "Monday, 16 April 1979", "date_str": "16/4/79", "text": "Easter Monday. Today I worked on my cars cooling system again. This time it appears that the temperature sensor is faulty so my fears of an imminent steam explosion were unfounded. Yesterday afternoon we travelled to Victor Harbour to spend the afternoon fishing. Mark and Laura both caught over a dozen sprat Tommy Ruffs and were almost deliriously happy. Their happiness was at least partly due to the difficulties that others were having in catching even one fish! The Tommies were miserably small but I dutifully filleted them and they ate them for breakfast today. The weather at Victor Harbour was almost eerily beautiful. Still, warm, clear and with an almost motionless sea. We stayed until dusk and had a barbecue tea in the dark on the beach near the causeway. We also saw nesting penguins under some of the rocks on Granite Island so that the day was a resounding success.", "page_ids": [100], "scan_page_ids": [100], "prediction_ids": ["P100_L1", "P100_L2", "P100_L3", "P100_L4"]}, {"index": 48, "date_display": "Saturday, 21 April 1979", "date_str": "21/4/79", "text": "VOTING - Thoughts on. In a stable situation the vote should reflect The realities of power and the determination)to use force and corction. If it does us it becomes an effective substitute for force and coercion in the political arena. If it does not it invites overthrow of the political system in a revolutionary way, or more applicable to the Australian scene in a piece-meal way Questionum is stability desirable? if so how cash the voting system be adapted to reflect the realities of power? with the current rapid rate of industrial and social development is it practical to attempt to develop a voting and representation system that reflects the realities of power?", "page_ids": [56], "scan_page_ids": [56], "prediction_ids": ["P56_L1", "P56_L2", "P56_L3", "P56_L4", "P56_L5", "P56_L6", "P56_L7", "P56_L8", "P56_L9", "P56_L10", "P56_L11"]}, {"index": 49, "date_display": "Friday, 27 April 1979", "date_str": "27/4/79", "text": "I have been re-reading the story of the Gracchi again (Daggers in the Forum) and browsing through a few other 'old faithful' books. This Week has been rather quiet and largely given over to a little experimental work and much back work at my desk. I have marked an interesting thesis by a student in Queensland working with Martin Lavin and Chev Kidson and have seen my article on Energy and life' appear in the 'Advertiser' on the 24th of this month. ($50 for the Thesis; $60 for the Advertiser article less an awful % tax.) In its some artifact of the media increasing the visibility of mass sex-motivated killers or are they actually becoming more concern on a world-wide scale? Our local horror stories seem to be slowly entering the world class, considering our population. (The Truro bodies)", "page_ids": [57, 58], "scan_page_ids": [57, 58], "prediction_ids": ["P57_L1", "P57_L2", "P57_L3", "P58_L1", "P58_L2", "P58_L3", "P58_L4", "P58_L5", "P58_L6", "P58_L7", "P58_L8", "P58_L9", "P58_L10"]}, {"index": 50, "date_display": "Saturday, 28 April 1979", "date_str": "28/4/79", "text": "Thoughts on reading the Saturday Australian. Most of my adult life I have tried to support a thoughtful , balanced approach to political issues and I have particularly despised the vast flood of 'moral people' who attempt to use psychological pressure to force all about them to conform to their horribly childish sets of beliefs. The most obvious and most effective of these groups was the Stalinist life that developed into the Trendy left. However, as noted by a columnist in the Australian, this wave is dying and a new firm of fashionable behaviour is becoming visibly effective. This could be described as Trendy rightism. At the moment it may be doing more good than harm as it is forcing the left to think instead of merely chanting however I fear that it will progress from a balanced pragmatism to a new form of cold blooded cruelty and neglect that will be described as allowing economic forces to run their course' or promoting an ‘invigorating bout of free enterprise’ I walked on the beach today. The weather was beautiful, the title high and the Surfies were out riding waves. When I look at all the young face brush but unsure of themselves, with their bodies about one decade away from beer-and-backcase obesity I have a feeling for the movement of time that refres my miniscule ambition. Those kids were rotund or shining little boys a decade ago and they will be notured or more rarely, skiing balding men in a decades time. With luck I will have twenty more papers to my credit and will be moving into the ‘grand old man or 'marvellous old character' category of scientists Well its damn site better fate to look towards to then most people have to look forward to", "page_ids": [59, 60, 61], "scan_page_ids": [59, 60], "prediction_ids": ["P59_L1", "P59_L2", "P59_L3", "P59_L4", "P59_L5", "P59_L6", "P59_L7", "P59_L8", "P59_L9", "P59_L10", "P59_L11", "P59_L12", "P59_L13", "P59_L14", "P59_L15", "P59_L16", "P60_L1", "P60_L2", "P60_L3", "P60_L4", "P60_L5", "P60_L6", "P60_L7", "P60_L8", "P60_L9", "P60_L10", "P61_L1"]}]}, {"month": 5, "month_name": "May", "entries": [{"index": 51, "date_display": "Saturday, 5 May 1979", "date_str": "5/5/79", "text": "Margaret Thatcher has just won the English election and I have hopes for her. However, as far as I am concerned, this would be the Tories last chance to be a viable alternative to a Union-labour party future I heard Arthur Kornberg speak last night and was slightly depressed by the realisation of how re-assured I was feeling off I was feeling ‘re-assured' then the doctrine of immediate results' must be very widespread induced. I was impressed by the clear way he described the present situation. If you apply for a grant you have a choice - (a) A brief application addressing yourself to a few limited points - This will fail to be supported. (b) A long horribly overambitious and pretensious application. This will get the money but fail to deliver useful results. I noticed Anne Levy was present - She is an ex Geneticist who has gone into politics. I hope the can do something practical about all this - particularly the shortage of post Doc positions in Australia.", "page_ids": [62], "scan_page_ids": [61], "prediction_ids": ["P62_L1", "P62_L2", "P62_L3", "P62_L4", "P62_L5", "P62_L6", "P62_L7", "P62_L8", "P62_L9", "P62_L10", "P62_L11", "P62_L12", "P62_L13", "P62_L14", "P62_L15", "P62_L16", "P62_L17", "P62_L18"]}, {"index": 52, "date_display": "Monday, 7 May 1979", "date_str": "7/5/79", "text": "Today I received a copy of 'Tall true tails of the Sea' by old Shell backs. Investigator Press Pty Ltd. 19 Kauri Road. Hawthornedean S.A. 5051. its strictly a collectors book being a hodge-podge of sea talks. However, one of the authors, Capt Maitland Thompson is an old friend of myself and my father and dad's name is frequently mentioned in one story - I will return ! Dad was a ships officer at this time and I was only a few years old. The ship they mention the Coringale, or perhaps more correctly Coringle, looms large in my childhood memories because it eventually returned to Adelaide and I spent some time on it during school holidays.", "page_ids": [63], "scan_page_ids": [62], "prediction_ids": ["P63_L1", "P63_L2", "P63_L3", "P63_L4", "P63_L5", "P63_L6", "P63_L7", "P63_L8", "P63_L9", "P63_L10"]}, {"index": 53, "date_display": "Saturday, 12 May 1979", "date_str": "12/5/79", "text": "Professor Hans Zachau landed in Adelaide the day before yesterday (ie. Thursday afternoon, Suppa) and John Wallace, from Adelaide university, now with me when we collected him John- Wallace is an enzymologist and is married to Pat Wallace who published a paper with me a few years ago on DNA polymerase. Hans Zachau seemed a quietly orderly gentleman with extremely from views that were charmingly, but shallowly, concealed. We had a dinner at the 'Steak Cellar' in Adelaide and those present were myself, Hans, John, George Rogers (acting head of Adelaide Biochem), and Peter Ey an immunologist who was an honours student of mind We had an extremely enjoyable evening with lots of good talk, since and laughter. God knows what we talked about but it was only marginally concerned with Biochemistry and mainly dealt with money, institutions and academic politics. On Friday Hans and I had a very detailed discussion about over work on chromatin and it appears that his 100 base-pair repeat is an index of superstructure and may tell more about chromatin superstructure than nucleosome substructure. I talked to him about cavities and penetration studies, mainly Hans Zachau is bald and rather looks like a Sikh slightly lighter version of the actor Telly Savalis who plays in a T.V. series called Kojak. ( swear to God that I have never watched one of his ,always. I have just finished reading 'On human nature' by Edward. A Wilson. Harvard lempires 1978. I felt that this book was more concerned with being interesting rather than lucid. However it did continue the assault we Biologists are making on the great halls of dogma (ie. - the schools of 'liberal' arts) and ignorance. It is a pity that the author has such a florid vocabulary and insists on trying his hand at poetry-in-prose every now and again. I felt that this would have been a good book if it was about half the length.", "page_ids": [64, 65], "scan_page_ids": [63, 64], "prediction_ids": ["P64_L1", "P64_L2", "P64_L3", "P64_L4", "P64_L5", "P64_L6", "P64_L7", "P64_L8", "P64_L9", "P64_L10", "P64_L11", "P64_L12", "P64_L13", "P64_L14", "P64_L15", "P64_L16", "P64_L17", "P64_L18", "P64_L19", "P64_L20", "P64_L21", "P64_L22", "P64_L23", "P64_L24", "P64_L25", "P65_L1", "P65_L2", "P65_L3", "P65_L4", "P65_L5", "P65_L6", "P65_L7"]}, {"index": 54, "date_display": "Tuesday, 15 May 1979", "date_str": "15/5/79", "text": "I am writing this at Burton College in Canberra. I am at the Australian Biochemistry Society meeting and this is the first full day. Yesterday I flew from Adelaide to Canberra on an aircraft that seemed full of Biochemists and we all fought with each other over the limited supply of taxis at the Canberra airport. All the way from the airport to the college I cursed the obvious ‘richmus' of the road work and buildings. The blasted politicians certainly dont stint themselves! this morning opened with a talk on urease and calcified tissue proteins that I didn't much enjoy A little later I tried to get into the Genetic-engineering-type session, and couldn't. The room was too small and the atmosphere too fetid. They really should assign more space to the more popular sessions. After lunch I posted my poster, worked around a little to see others and then attended Koonberg's lecture on DNA-synthesis - proteins. (Arthur Kornberg ie. Kimbery, Senior) Kormberg's lecture was fearfully impressive and a testimony to mass determination to always I have spoken to Ken Gaylor (an old friend from undergraduate days), Peter Hudson (who I knew in Adelaide and Cambridge) Cyryl Appleby, Peter Rees ( he told me how he had run a racing book at school), Hanss Zachau, a large number of my standard, Adelaide, friends and sundry others I have just left the 'mixer' . This is a liquor's sacks party at which ‘every body is supposed to get to know each other and it is a traditional first night affair.", "page_ids": [66], "scan_page_ids": [65], "prediction_ids": ["P66_L1", "P66_L2", "P66_L3", "P66_L4", "P66_L5", "P66_L6", "P66_L7", "P66_L8", "P66_L9", "P66_L10", "P66_L11", "P66_L12", "P66_L13", "P66_L14", "P66_L15", "P66_L16", "P66_L17", "P66_L18", "P66_L19", "P66_L20", "P66_L21", "P66_L22", "P66_L23", "P66_L24", "P66_L25"]}, {"index": 55, "date_display": "Wednesday, 16 May 1979", "date_str": "16/5/79", "text": "A moderately successful day. However John-Wheldrake and myself are planning on flying home one day sooner. ie on Thursday, tomorrow, evening rather than Friday evening I attended some of the arom pathway lectures and heard Cyryl Appleby's talk on oxygen lemon, leghaemoglobin and nitrogenase. The college cooking is beginning to pall a little I saw one of TV personalities Noel Ferrier, I think: a rather heavy man who played the old husband in the film 'Eliza Fraser'", "page_ids": [67, 68], "scan_page_ids": [66, 67, 68], "prediction_ids": ["P67_L1", "P67_L2", "P68_L1", "P68_L2", "P68_L3", "P68_L4", "P68_L5", "P69_L1"]}, {"index": 56, "date_display": "Monday, 21 May 1979", "date_str": "21/5/79", "text": "I have been home 4 days ago and Judy returned with the kids yesterday. They all a great deal of fun on the farm and Mark was overjoyed at being allowed to drive the 'utility' that Bert & Ray had just purchased. Susan, my sister, is on the brink of giving birth and we are all waiting with bated breath for the great moment. We head lunch with her today at West-lakes and I spent sometime gently massaging her distended abdomen as it seemed to give her some relief from her discomfort. I also went to Captain Thompson's house to visit him but he was not home so I took the kids to the merry-go-round instead. Mark refused to ride on such a childish device and instead, got cheated at the 'lucky dip' him We returned to Seaford, had tea, watched a little TN (Plus and 'Are you being served' ) and I made a small, demonstration batch of gun-porter for Mark. I had promised to do this last night when Laura, Mark and Myself were cooking cheese over a small fire in the front yard and I had demonstrated the old regards trick of throwing potassium nitrate on the coats. I shipped through an 'Angelique' novel by Sergeanne Godon last night but didn't get much pleasure out of it.", "page_ids": [69], "scan_page_ids": [69], "prediction_ids": ["P69_L2", "P69_L3", "P69_L4", "P69_L5", "P69_L6", "P69_L7", "P69_L8", "P69_L9", "P69_L10", "P69_L11", "P69_L12", "P69_L13", "P69_L14", "P69_L15", "P69_L16", "P69_L17", "P69_L18", "P69_L19", "P69_L20"]}, {"index": 57, "date_display": "Tuesday, 29 May 1979", "date_str": "29/5/79", "text": "Our house modifications are nearly finished and I will be making the final payment soon. Yesterday (or the day before yesterday?) I listened to a Canadian visitor discussing Neurospora nucleases and their relation to recombination and repair mutants. We had a long discussion about nucleases generally and although I have temporally forgotten his name, I found the discussion quite interesting (name-Murray Fraser (from McGill university)] I have a mild but persistent and 'deep' cold. My lungs are affected so that I have to cough frequently but I am not systemically affected. The last 5 days have been rather boringly devoted to marking perspectives in Biology' papers and assembling the work scores for my section of the course.", "page_ids": [70], "scan_page_ids": [70], "prediction_ids": ["P70_L1", "P70_L2", "P70_L3", "P70_L4", "P70_L5", "P70_L6", "P70_L7", "P70_L8", "P70_L9", "P70_L10", "P70_L11"]}]}, {"month": 6, "month_name": "June", "entries": [{"index": 58, "date_display": "Saturday, 2 June 1979", "date_str": "2/6/79", "text": "I have just finished reading a book that John Wheldrake loaned me called Mediterranean - a portrait ofases' by Erie Bradford It was thoroughly enjoyable and I was quite sorry when I finished reading it. Its a sort of overview of the Mediterranean's history from prehistoric times until ~ today. However it was not merely a condensed history because the man’ s love for his subject so ‘illuminated‘ his work that it became a real pleasure to share his obvious pleasure. I still have my cough and I am thoroughly sick of the dreary cycle of irritation-cough-irritation.", "page_ids": [71], "scan_page_ids": [71], "prediction_ids": ["P71_L1", "P71_L2", "P71_L3", "P71_L4", "P71_L5", "P71_L6", "P71_L7", "P71_L8", "P71_L9", "P71_L10"]}, {"index": 59, "date_display": "Tuesday, 5 June 1979", "date_str": "5/6/79", "text": "Still coughing, dammit. I have been taking things quietly in an attempt to get rid of the cough. A few days ago my Aunty Phil Bedford (my mothers sister, maiden name - Parker) recovered my old, childhood encyclopedias. Mother had given them to Andy Bedford (Aunties child, my cousin) when it appeared that I was no longer using them and now, as they were getting even older and I suspected Andy was no longer using them I 'genteely' asked for their return. I hope that they were no longer wanted by Andy but I cant really be absolutely sure. However, I dont regret asking for them back as it has been an enormous pleasure to read the old familiar 'potted' histories and biographies; and an even greater pleasure to look at the illustrations even if they are only in black and white. It was published as 'Richards topical Encyclopedia' 1949, J.A.Richards publishing Co, printed and Bound by Kingsport Press, Inc Kingsport Tenn. and it had been reprinted at almost yearly intervals since 1933., with obvious updatings This set of books was almost my full exposure to CULTURE!! for many years and I remember how much I depended on these books during the constant attacks of Bronchial Asthma I suffered through my childhood & teens. My children have had a look through them and seem to heartily approve of them so perhaps they will have another generation of use yet", "page_ids": [72], "scan_page_ids": [72], "prediction_ids": ["P72_L1", "P72_L2", "P72_L3", "P72_L4", "P72_L5", "P72_L6", "P72_L7", "P72_L8", "P72_L9", "P72_L10", "P72_L11", "P72_L12", "P72_L13", "P72_L14", "P72_L15", "P72_L16", "P72_L17", "P72_L18", "P72_L19", "P72_L20", "P72_L21", "P72_L22"]}, {"index": 60, "date_display": "Sunday, 10 June 1979", "date_str": "10/6/79", "text": "I am still coughing. I have had a rather quiet weekend Susan (my sister) has had her daughter, by Caesarian section, on friday and on Friday night Judy and I attended a medical sciences club seminar, sheet attached below, after which we visited Anne and John Wheldrake for coffee This week-end I have made a large 'trestle' for the girls to practice their beam-walking, I have aided in the girls regular campfire adventure, cut some wood for our bathroom cabinet, and electrically fixed one of Mark's model rockets. The campfire was a success, as usual, and the girls managed to cook a satisfactory number of sausages for themselves. The Rocket flew magnificently although the motor only burned for about a second or two However the thrust was quite enough to throw it, dismayed night across our kindergarten reserve and at the height of its trajectory it must have been at least 100 metres\n\nup. The Medical Sciences CUTB OF SOUTH AUSTRALIA", "page_ids": [73, 74], "scan_page_ids": [73, 74], "prediction_ids": ["P73_L1", "P73_L2", "P73_L3", "P74_L1", "P74_L2", "P74_L3", "P74_L4", "P74_L5", "P74_L6", "P74_L7", "P74_L8", "P74_L9", "P74_L10", "P74_L11", "P74_L12", "P74_L13", "P74_L14"]}, {"index": 61, "date_display": "Sunday, 17 June 1979", "date_str": "17/6/79", "text": "Sunday. I am still coughing. I have had an industrious' week that has been made a little unpleasant by a continual cough which has made lecturing quite unpleasant. On Friday Judy myself and the kids visited the central market and then visited Susan in the Calvary hospital maternity ward The major news this week - Malaya's grim statements about its attitude to the Vietnamese is making every-one think about the whole situation a little more. I cant help think that we are slowly moving into an age where 'ideological differences' are going to be used as an excuse for population-dumping or disposal. This ruse is getting increasingly transparent and history may record the great flood of Bengalie, East-Pakistan’ into India as the first obvious use of this ruse. What are we to do with people that are first ejected and then tossed like football from country to country not entirely because they are unwanted but also because no country wants to mark itself as a 'soft victim' for this sort of off-loading of population excess. Europe did this, in a 'slightly disguised way, during the 19th & early 20th Century but now there are no political vaccuums to dump excess population into. Moreover the compound interest arithmetic of population increase indicates that population shifting will only give a trivial, temporary chiefreligious On Friday I sent a letter to the minister of transport (State) about the rule forbidding Surfies taking their surf boards onto buses. I pointed out that this was encouraging hitchhiking in a rather vulnerable group of people. myself and I am dawn sure I am not going to demand it from others.", "page_ids": [75, 76], "scan_page_ids": [75, 76], "prediction_ids": ["P75_L1", "P75_L2", "P75_L3", "P75_L4", "P75_L5", "P75_L6", "P75_L7", "P75_L8", "P75_L9", "P75_L10", "P75_L11", "P75_L12", "P75_L13", "P75_L14", "P75_L15", "P75_L16", "P75_L17", "P75_L18", "P75_L19", "P75_L20", "P75_L21", "P75_L22", "P75_L23", "P75_L24", "P75_L25", "P76_L1", "P76_L2"]}, {"index": 62, "date_display": "Thursday, 21 June 1979", "date_str": "21/6/79", "text": "On Monday (the 18th) I lightly hit the tail bumper of another car at Morphetvale. Name of my 'victim'  H. Keenan, 7 Maskard Rd, Morphetvale, phone 3823769. I am, at present, negotiating the cost of the damages. Thank goodness that I have finally stopped coughing. I can thus go for a jog tonight and fight the dogs off again. I have just finished reading a book Judy got for me; so nice to have a considerate wife! Title - 'The Salisbury Affair' by Stewart Cockburn. I quite enjoyed it and, more or less, swallowed its thesis. However I feel that a modern democracy demands too much of its leaders and despite Dunstan's 'manoeuvres' I suspect he was pretty well making the best he could out of a poor situation. I don't expect perfect judgement in", "page_ids": [102], "scan_page_ids": [102], "prediction_ids": ["P102_L1", "P102_L2"]}, {"index": 63, "date_display": "Tuesday, 26 June 1979", "date_str": "26/6/79", "text": "Work is grinding on It is horrifying how much time is spent dithering around writing and checking grant applications. Day by day the stories of the Vietnam and Cambodian refugees continues to fill the news, and so it should. I think most of us remember on have read about all the excuses people had for not accepting jews from NAZI Germany and yet there is the fear that this flood of refugees is only the beginning of a series of similar floods as the worlds overcrowded countries push out their politically difficult’ and their socially superfluous.", "page_ids": [77], "scan_page_ids": [77], "prediction_ids": ["P77_L1", "P77_L2", "P77_L3", "P77_L4", "P77_L5", "P77_L6", "P77_L7", "P77_L8", "P77_L9"]}]}, {"month": 7, "month_name": "July", "entries": [{"index": 64, "date_display": "Wednesday, 4 July 1979", "date_str": "4/7/79", "text": "The weather has been very cold and I am working my way through essays and a grant proposal . I am going to ask the U.S. N.I.H. for support I.D.Bitty Ltd for one Post Doctoral student I had a slightly strange experience today. One of my mature-age students from last years 'Perspectives in Biology' class took me out to lunch. We had a business-mans lunch with one of his friends and just generally discussed current topics. Both men were about 40 and ex Army 'buddies'. Both had been in Vietnam and had actually enjoyed their tour of duty there. The students name was Graham Davidson working for Paul Terry insurance services, what ever that may be. His friends just name was Lee and he was some sort of management staff for a car hire firm. Letz rentacar. The nominal motive for the dinner was rather interesting. They apparently have these lunches as consciousness-broadening exercises. The days guest is supposed to broaden their outlook and their circle of acquaintances and this seems a very enlightened attitude. However I couldn't help wondering, just a little bit if this wasn't some gentle probing strategy used by one of the security depts such as ASIO. I do not have anything against National security agencies and I am most certainly not anti-ASIO on principle however it is a little interesting thought. If this totally innocent dinner was a probing exercise. I suspect I must be confusing ASIO does a paid up member of the Council of Civil liberties have such ‘rightist views?’ I have just flicked through a book on Slaves and Freedmen in reconstruction Louisiana and last Friday I spoke to Enfield high school students at a camp for final year students at MYLOR Baptist youth camp; I spoke on Tumour Biochemistry", "page_ids": [78, 79], "scan_page_ids": [78, 79], "prediction_ids": ["P78_L1", "P78_L2", "P78_L3", "P78_L4", "P78_L5", "P78_L6", "P78_L7", "P78_L8", "P78_L9", "P78_L10", "P78_L11", "P78_L12", "P78_L13", "P78_L14", "P78_L15", "P78_L16", "P78_L17", "P78_L18", "P78_L19", "P78_L20", "P78_L21", "P78_L22", "P78_L23", "P78_L24", "P79_L1", "P79_L2", "P79_L3", "P79_L4", "P79_L5"]}, {"index": 65, "date_display": "Saturday, 7 July 1979", "date_str": "7/7/79", "text": "Last night Judy and I spent a very enjoyable evening with dinner at Anne and John Wheldrake’s place. There were a number of other guests who were Anne's fellow medical students Most of the evening was spent in a very animated and satisfying argument about current events in South East Asia. I was claiming that North Vietnam was getting away with policies that very few other countries would be able to implement without massive international protest. One of the students was claiming that Vietnam’s policies were quite ‘ understandable‘ considering her economic difficulties. He was probably right , but I bet no other nation would be extended that loving understanding.", "page_ids": [80], "scan_page_ids": [80], "prediction_ids": ["P80_L1", "P80_L2", "P80_L3", "P80_L4", "P80_L5", "P80_L6", "P80_L7", "P80_L8", "P80_L9", "P80_L10", "P80_L11", "P80_L12"]}, {"index": 66, "date_display": "Wednesday, 11 July 1979", "date_str": "11/7/79", "text": "The whole household is either ill or recovering from illness. Mark and Laura are recovering from head colds, Kirsty has some sort of gut infection and has vomited, and Judy has a serious tonsil infection and is in bed. I am, for once, triumphantly healthy! America's Skylab is due to come to earth tonight and we are all waiting, expectantly, for news of the pieces. I have just thoroughly read a book on the effect of transport on Australia called 'The Tyranny of distance' by G. Blainey and I enjoyed it. I have also browsed through an old book on the history of Attila and his Huns. However it was a wee bit too scholarly for my tastes and I was a little annoyed by the sections like in untranslated Latin or Greek even though they were minor.", "page_ids": [81], "scan_page_ids": [81], "prediction_ids": ["P81_L1", "P81_L2", "P81_L3", "P81_L4", "P81_L5", "P81_L6", "P81_L7", "P81_L8", "P81_L9", "P81_L10", "P81_L11", "P81_L12", "P81_L13"]}, {"index": 67, "date_display": "Wednesday, 18 July 1979", "date_str": "18/7/79", "text": "My ‘Triumphant’ health collapsed the following day when a very severe bout of enteric trouble sent me scuttling to the local doctor for sympathy & potions. I watch about an hour of TV an evening on average. I mainly watch comedies and a few documentaries. Tonight I watched 'Adall titles were part in Liu de Hall' his Spike Milliance and first matter. My part in his downfall by Spike Milligan and quite", "page_ids": [82, 83], "scan_page_ids": [82, 83], "prediction_ids": ["P82_L1", "P82_L2", "P82_L3", "P82_L4", "P82_L5", "P83_L1", "P83_L2"]}, {"index": 68, "date_display": "Thursday, 19 July 1979", "date_str": "19/7/79", "text": "I am writing this while standing in front of the gas-heater. I have been quietly reflecting on the fuel shortages this evening. At long last many people are beginning to have the vague unsettled feeling that something important is happening This evening I filled the tank of my Datsun 120Y and it cost me the horrific sum of $9! I only hope that people respond to these prices by economising on fuel and not merely by demanding more wages. I have just read and thoroughly enjoyed, 'Myself a mandarin' by Austin Coates (Heineman publl.). It describes the experiences of an English Magistrate administering a district of Hong Kong I flicked through but did not closely read, 'The Devil' by and. R.F.M. Jeffrey Burton Russell", "page_ids": [84], "scan_page_ids": [84], "prediction_ids": ["P84_L1", "P84_L2", "P84_L3", "P84_L4", "P84_L5", "P84_L6", "P84_L7", "P84_L8", "P84_L9", "P84_L10", "P84_L11", "P84_L12", "P84_L13", "P84_L14"]}, {"index": 69, "date_display": "Monday, 30 July 1979", "date_str": "30/7/79", "text": "Today I made arrangements to see a lawyer about another minor accident to my car name was R.Marshall 332-6295 and she was referred to me by Anne Tonkin (Wheldrake). Yesterday evening I had dinner at Susans to celebrate Laura’s birthday . Gilbert Calaby and I discussed ‘ Blood-worms ‘ during the evening. These worm leave the mud and swim out to sea for about 2 nights a year and on the 28th of this month (28/7/79) they were strongly 'running'. This is apparently two weeks later than last year. They are found swimming in the Port River, generally in trails of reed rather than open water . Gil says they are generally caught from dredge wharf to the fare-way beacon out in deep water. ( croft) and seem to be heading out to sea. However they did not appear to be in as far as West-Lakes - so Gil says. I have purchased a month’s bus tickets and will give the bus system a good try . My last accident has quite taken away much of the pleasure of motoring and the ratio of fuel prices to bus fares is also persuasive at the moment. On Saturday (28/7/79) Laura and Sharon (her friend) had another ‘camp-fire ‘ in the front yard and they cooked thick banana slices. ufting Yesterday and", "page_ids": [85], "scan_page_ids": [85], "prediction_ids": ["P85_L1", "P85_L2", "P85_L3", "P85_L4", "P85_L5", "P85_L6", "P85_L7", "P85_L8", "P85_L9", "P85_L10", "P85_L11", "P85_L12", "P85_L13", "P85_L14", "P85_L15", "P85_L16", "P85_L17", "P85_L18", "P85_L19"]}]}, {"month": 8, "month_name": "August", "entries": [{"index": 70, "date_display": "Wednesday, 1 August 1979", "date_str": "1/8/79", "text": "today a minor bench-mark has been passed in our times. Judy and I went up to our new room to take up 'Residence' and the children each got their own room Laura is in the South West corner room of the bottom floor of the house. Kirsty is in Mark's old room which is the middle bedroom on the South side bottom floor. Mark is in his own room which is the South-east, ground floor bedroom. The quote for the repairs to my car was $695.37, Lonsdale crash repairs ; Prop Bill Hawkes . I also obtained a second quote, for legal reasons from Christies Beach crash repairs. However Christies Crash repairs made no secret of the fact that they wouldn't undercut the other firm so it was hardly a fair secondgate. Nevertheless the price was about what I expected to I am not going to go through the farce of getting more quotes.", "page_ids": [86], "scan_page_ids": [86], "prediction_ids": ["P86_L1", "P86_L2", "P86_L3", "P86_L4", "P86_L5", "P86_L6", "P86_L7", "P86_L8", "P86_L9", "P86_L10", "P86_L11", "P86_L12", "P86_L13"]}, {"index": 71, "date_display": "Sunday, 5 August 1979", "date_str": "5/8/79", "text": "Sunday Evening. This has been a cold and wet weekend to I have occupied myself with work around the house and reading. I am reading 'The Spanish Inquisition' by Jean Plaidy and I have found it absorbing reading although rather unpleasant reading", "page_ids": [87], "scan_page_ids": [87], "prediction_ids": ["P87_L1", "P87_L2", "P87_L3", "P87_L4", "P87_L5"]}, {"index": 72, "date_display": "Sunday, 12 August 1979", "date_str": "12/8/79", "text": "Sunday afternoon. Last night we had a dinner with Bill & Liz Lawson. They brought their daughter, Jessica, with them and the is an extremely vivacious child who obviously enjoyed mixing with our older children The dinner was a moderate success although there seemed some slight personal tension between Liz & Bill. Liz has multiple Sclerosis and Bill has a weight-heart problem so together they must find it difficult to keep their family of 3 running smoothly ( 3 two parents +t Jessica) Bill and I rather listlessly discussed state politics as he is a staunch Labour supporter and I enjoy discussions with any representative' of the soundry political groups in this State . Bill works as a publicity or information officer for the E.W.S. and he is a moderately close personal acquaintance of Peter Duncan one of the present ministers of the State government I am not an admirer of Peter Duncan but it is interesting to hear some of the Labour party gossip. There is apparently much amusement at present as Peter Duncan has married an extremely 'Busty' and attractive Tasmanian girl and people are wondering how long this will less On Friday night (The 10th) Judy and I attended the medical sciences club meeting (below) and listened to Da Coulter deliver a routing season against nuclear power. He was laden with facts and references but ended up with a solidly hostile audience. However we all had a chance to air our views", "page_ids": [88, 89], "scan_page_ids": [88, 89], "prediction_ids": ["P88_L1", "P88_L2", "P88_L3", "P88_L4", "P88_L5", "P88_L6", "P88_L7", "P88_L8", "P88_L9", "P88_L10", "P88_L11", "P88_L12", "P88_L13", "P88_L14", "P88_L15", "P88_L16", "P89_L1", "P89_L2", "P89_L3", "P89_L4", "P89_L5", "P89_L6", "P89_L7", "P89_L8"]}, {"index": 73, "date_display": "Sunday, 19 August 1979", "date_str": "19/8/79", "text": "A relatively uneventful week. On Thursday I had my ARGC interviews and it seemed to be satisfactory but nobody knows how much money the ARGC is going to have to distribute so I hope it wasn't all in vain. I have also sent an application off to the U.S. NI.H in an attempt to get a post Doctoral Student. My sister, Susan, visited we yesterday to show off the new baby again and I have begun my beach walks again. On Judy and I went to 'The Mikado' and enjoyed it. At the moment (645 pm) the house reeks of garlic because Mark made a mistake and put a large sliced garlic in the stew instead of an onion. Our tea is going to be something of an adventure!", "page_ids": [90], "scan_page_ids": [90], "prediction_ids": ["P90_L1", "P90_L2", "P90_L3", "P90_L4", "P90_L5", "P90_L6", "P90_L7", "P90_L8", "P90_L9", "P90_L10"]}]}, {"month": 9, "month_name": "September", "entries": [{"index": 74, "date_display": "Saturday, 1 September 1979", "date_str": "1/9/79", "text": "The last month of my 39th year. I am writing this on my in-laws farm at Corryton Park sitting in front of an old-fashioned open fire. There are high, old Eucalypts all around the house yard and amongst them there is the remnants of the old bush undergrowth. I have had a very sequestered week eating, reading a little (mainly very cheap novels and magazines) and I have spent much time marking exam papers. I am marking - 'Biological Information', 'Perspectives in Biology', and Introduction to Cell and Molecular Biology'. These are 3rd yr Biology, 1st year Arts-Biology and 2nd year Arts-Biology respectively. Judy, Laura and Kirsty have spent the week at a Brownies camp at Robe. Judy helped organise and cater while the two girls had a 'wow' of a time Mark has mainly been involved with farm work! He is becoming quite a useful help to his uncle Ray and is now quite proficient at hand- millasing even! P.S. I am also writing a small Fortran programme for David Catchesides fungal work.", "page_ids": [91], "scan_page_ids": [91], "prediction_ids": ["P91_L1", "P91_L2", "P91_L3", "P91_L4", "P91_L5", "P91_L6", "P91_L7", "P91_L8", "P91_L9", "P91_L10", "P91_L11", "P91_L12", "P91_L13", "P91_L14", "P91_L15", "P91_L16", "P91_L17"]}, {"index": 75, "date_display": "Sunday, 16 September 1979", "date_str": "16/9/79", "text": "The election is over and the Liberals have won with a comfortable majority. The disaster started looming up for Labour a couple of days ago when the business groups all started an anti- labour campaign and the bus-driver strike was not resolved. Strictly the bus drivers did not strike but rather carried out a programme of random disruption of schedules I spent yesterday morning in my house's ceiling repairing on old air-conditioner and I have spent this morning re assembling an old cupboard in the upstairs study. I have just finished a long, pleasurable, re-read of Robert Graves translation of the Golden Ass' by Apuleius. In a couple of days time I will offer it to David Moore to read. He is a student public service employee I often meet when commuting. The weather is bright, ween and the Murray magpies are attacking this train Images in our window again", "page_ids": [93], "scan_page_ids": [93], "prediction_ids": ["P93_L2", "P93_L3", "P93_L4", "P93_L5", "P93_L6", "P93_L7", "P93_L8", "P93_L9", "P93_L10", "P93_L11", "P93_L12", "P93_L13", "P93_L14", "P93_L15", "P93_L16", "P93_L17"]}, {"index": 76, "date_display": "Saturday, 22 September 1979", "date_str": "22/9/79", "text": "The Adelaide Canon Research group met last night and John. Subine spoke. To be Frank, the meeting was a dead bore. We 1 discussed more on less dated concepts and indulged ourselves with corny academic jokes and technical point scoring. I cant even say I was totally innocent of this sort of shallow folly myself. However I felt that it was particularly unacceptable last night because ‘the convenor of the meeting, Leonie Ashman, had just lost her husband to a brain tumour and I heard that his final weeks were pretty unpleasant. Leonie didn't attend last, nights meeting and I cant say I blame her. She has indicated, previously, that she didn't have a great deal of respect for the cancer work being done in this state, or indeed, elsewhere. So its hardly likely that she would feel like attending one of our little ego pumping shows with its shallow 'profundities' just after her husband has died. Although I am not quite as depressed about cancer research as Leonie it cannot be denied that most cancer researchers are careerists first, and truth hunters second. Moreover the regular meeting of various cancer groups are mainly used as opportunities to impress any of ones peers that might possibly be refereeing ones grant applications. Today is my 40th birthday and this evening we have invited the following to dinner - Tory & Cynthia Ruthfen ; Jenny Skinner and Keith Dixon ; John and Anne Wheldrake; and my Sister Susan This morning I drove Mark a Laura in to their regular ‘drama' classes at Carclew house in North Adelaide. I marked essays while they jumped and francid Mauk attended Syr. today as usual and is probably going to start attending Sundays too The weather is warm, sunny and beautiful; I feel happy and feel that life is 'good'!", "page_ids": [94], "scan_page_ids": [103], "prediction_ids": ["P94_L1", "P94_L2", "P94_L3", "P94_L4", "P94_L5", "P94_L6", "P94_L7", "P94_L8", "P94_L9", "P94_L10", "P94_L11", "P94_L12", "P94_L13", "P94_L14", "P94_L15", "P94_L16", "P94_L17", "P94_L18", "P94_L19", "P94_L20", "P94_L21", "P94_L22", "P94_L23", "P94_L24", "P94_L25", "P94_L26", "P94_L27", "P94_L28", "P94_L29", "P94_L30", "P94_L31"]}, {"index": 77, "date_display": "Saturday, 22 September 1979", "date_str": "22/9/79", "text": "I attended this Thursday meeting last night. Discussion — below. Adelaide Cancer Research Group. The speaker will be Dr. John Sabine, Dept. of Animal Physiology, Waite Institute. 'Neodifferentiation, unfamiliar polypeptides and miscreant membranes: a new theory of the biology of carcinogenesis'. Note — Leonie Ashman's husband Ken Ashman died the other day of a brain tumour. Note — Ian Forbes was present.", "page_ids": [103], "scan_page_ids": [103], "prediction_ids": ["P103_L1"]}, {"index": 78, "date_display": "Sunday, 30 September 1979", "date_str": "30/9/79", "text": "Sunday night. Last night we had Andy Murray and his wife Jan and Rod Wells and his wife Alice down for dinner. held had a pleasant evening discussing 'social reform, politicians and the perfidity of the 'forces of darkness' at work in the Registry. We considered the possibility of getting the academics to F'gang-up' on the registry the trouble is we all work too hard to plot and Plan while ‘then‘ have waste amounts of time to plan their nasty looking book over this Journal I note that I make us, or very few revealing comments about my own sexual life and feelings Generally the word 'Frankly' precedes a deuption! I feel that the late twentieth century is far too intellectually concerned with sex. They, or we, over rate its real importance to many higher functions. Sex is enormously enjoyable, enormously commercially important and provides the motivation for some of many interest actarities as well as many apparently 'sensible' activities. It underlies much of our ambition and is providing us with a major portion of our recreation. However it is just an evolutionary programmed ‘erational drive that distracts an enormous amount of attention from productive national thought. Probably its best clear properly ib its ability to provide a pleasant emotional accompaniment to an intellectual other type of friendshipor partnership All in all I suspect any future reader of this journal would be wasting his time if I dutifully entered up the weekly details of my fantasies and pleasures. Moreover if I did enter them up I would have to hide this book or use some sort of code. South Australia is a small state. Last night was all examined the web of our friendships and wondered how many modern states are small enough for three relatively undestinguished academies to have had personal contact with both the present premier and Don Dunstan. I have just finished reading 'Victorian England- as seen by Punch’ by Frank E. Huggett. Its a little sad as its more or less an account of the slow decay of English power. I am not an ardent empiricalist but it is still-moving' to watch any great creature grow old and die. Long live the new England!! when it can finally sort out its present indecicians). note - Tony Rathjen gave this book to me at my Birthday party last Saturday.", "page_ids": [95, 96], "scan_page_ids": [94, 95], "prediction_ids": ["P95_L1", "P95_L2", "P95_L3", "P95_L4", "P95_L5", "P95_L6", "P96_L1", "P96_L2", "P96_L3", "P96_L4", "P96_L5", "P96_L6", "P96_L7", "P96_L8", "P96_L9", "P96_L10", "P96_L11", "P96_L12", "P96_L13", "P96_L14", "P96_L15", "P96_L16", "P96_L17", "P96_L18", "P96_L19", "P96_L20", "P96_L21", "P96_L22", "P96_L23", "P96_L24", "P96_L25", "P96_L26", "P96_L27", "P96_L28", "P96_L29", "P96_L30", "P96_L31"]}]}, {"month": 10, "month_name": "October", "entries": [{"index": 79, "date_display": "Thursday, 4 October 1979", "date_str": "4/10/79", "text": "I attended and enjoyed the Medical Sciences Club meeting (See opposite). I had a long talk with Eleanor Atkinson at the relatively sumptuous supper provided between sessions. After the meeting I drove Rupert Best home to Moana and we discussed the dangers of resurgent religions of the fundamentalist Type. Rupert is an old, retired biochemistry lecturer who worked at the Wait institute during my under graduate years. Eleanor Atkinson is the daughter of my old professor and mentor', Maurice Atkinson", "page_ids": [97, 98], "scan_page_ids": [96, 97], "prediction_ids": ["P97_L1", "P97_L2", "P97_L3", "P97_L4", "P97_L5", "P98_L1", "P98_L2", "P98_L3"]}, {"index": 80, "date_display": "Monday, 8 October 1979", "date_str": "8/10/79", "text": "The monday holiday. One of our gums, the candle-bark was badly loosened by the heavy winds that we have had in the last few days. So I have been occupied cutting off its larger boughs in preparation for its complete removal. As usual, Laura went berserk using the branches to build a 'cubby house' and, also as usual, I pulled the cubby house down as soon as she was out of sight. I have also laid out some Daphne cuttings in my room and planted some tomatoe seeds. (hormone, fungicide, treated) Tomorrow I am going out to the Northfield Pig Research Farm again to get Semen. # Note — The tomato strain I've planted is 'Super Marmande'.", "page_ids": [104], "scan_page_ids": [98], "prediction_ids": ["P104_L1", "P104_L2", "P104_L3"]}, {"index": 81, "date_display": "Wednesday, 10 October 1979", "date_str": "10/10/79", "text": "Its being claimed that about one million people died in the flow of refugees from Vietnam to nearby countries by sea. I shall be interested in future years to see if this estimate is supported or turns out to be an exaggeration (or worse still an underestimate.) My state, south Australia is in the grip of election fever and the betting is that the Labour party will win but I think the Liberals have a much better chance than the pundits think so I shall be looking forward to the election results with great interest", "page_ids": [92, 93], "scan_page_ids": [92, 93], "prediction_ids": ["P92_L1", "P92_L2", "P92_L3", "P92_L4", "P92_L5", "P92_L6", "P92_L7", "P92_L8", "P93_L1"]}, {"index": 82, "date_display": "Wednesday, 17 October 1979", "date_str": "17/10/79", "text": "Today the tomatoe seeds have begun to germinate and emerge. My research is going slowly as teaching is consuming an inordinately large amount of time. Moreover I am increasingly convinced that much of this time is wasted. We are trying to provide too many teaching services of low value and failing to direct enough resources to the quality of the lecturing and research. I am tired — tired — tired. I like lecturing but I feel that the university is wasting much of my effort by directing it to excessive assessment and endless 'supplementary' exams.", "page_ids": [105], "scan_page_ids": [104], "prediction_ids": ["P105_L1", "P105_L2"]}, {"index": 83, "date_display": "Monday, 22 October 1979", "date_str": "22/10/79", "text": "Last night (Sunday) Judy and I spent the evening at John & Anne Wheldrake's house at a dinner celebrating her birthday. The State Premier David Tonkin, and his wife Prue were the other two guests We had a quietly pleasant evening with good food and quiet pleasant conversation. The subjects were mainly medical or light-political. We were all too tired or relaxed for any conversations of consequence. Probably the only point worth noting is the discussion on the likely political consequences of a major atomic accident and the way it might pressure the uranium development plans. I emphasised the probably difficulties and the 'good Dr' down-played them, at least", "page_ids": [99], "scan_page_ids": [99, 105], "prediction_ids": ["P99_L1", "P99_L2", "P99_L3", "P99_L4", "P99_L5", "P99_L6", "P99_L7", "P99_L8", "P99_L9", "P99_L10"]}]}]}], "summaries": {"years": {"1978": "May to November at Flinders University: lab work on micrococcal nuclease conjugation, DEC-10 programming, and a busy mid-year teaching grind. A family holiday at the Watson farm near Lucindale is a highlight. Voracious reading (Yourcenar, Marcus Aurelius, Procopius), concern over unemployment and university funding, and China's post-Mao shifts run through the months. Leigh turns 39 and applies for a readership.", "1979": "A year of milestones. A major house extension is built and the family moves in by August. Distinguished visitors arrive at Flinders — Gurdon, Zachau, Kornberg, Stent. Easter fishing at Victor Harbour, campfires, and model rockets fill domestic life. The broader world intrudes through the China–Vietnam war, the refugee crisis, Thatcher's election, and Don Dunstan's resignation. Leigh turns 40, writes grant applications, and grows weary of excessive assessment."}, "months": {"1978-05": "The diary opens with Leigh deep in lab work (conjugating glycogen to micrococcal nuclease) and DEC-10 programming, while Judy and the children return from the farm where Mark has learned to drive. Beach walks at Seaford, and neighbours discussing spreading unemployment in South Australia.", "1978-06": "Intensely busy with lectures, DEC-10 programming, Intel 8080 study, and agarose column work. Leigh reads Yourcenar's 'Memoirs of Hadrian', dines with Jenny Skinner and Keith Dixon at Glenelg, and Ray Watson stays while wool-classing. The nuclease conjugation experiments begin yielding interpretable results.", "1978-07": "The mid-year teaching grind leaves little time for diary-keeping. Leigh sees Eric Sykes and Jimmy Edwards in 'Big Bad Mouse', hosts in-laws Bert and Lois Watson, and dines with Tony Rathjen who fears losing his Waite Institute job. Beach walks and Intel 8080 programming fill the gaps.", "1978-08": "Leigh finishes his 'Perspectives in Biology' seminars and worries about the federal budget's squeeze on universities. The highlight is a family holiday at the Watson farm near Lucindale — marking papers by the fire, spotting echidnas, walking sheep, and attending Ray's theatre production in Kingston.", "1978-09": "A quiet month dominated by a lingering cold and steady academic work. Leigh turns 39, reads Richmal Crompton's 'William' books and Seneca's 'Letters from a Stoic', and writes at length on China's post-Mao shifts and his ambivalence about judging students demoralised by unemployment.", "1978-10": "The cough clears and good weather returns. Leigh enjoys 'Against the Wind' on TV, attends a birthday party at the Tonkin home (father of colleague Anne Wheldrake) where political gossip flows, and notes the death of SA Premier's wife Adele Koh. Dinners with the Wheldrakes and Catchesides.", "1978-11": "Leigh reads Procopius' 'Secret History' and Marcus Aurelius' 'Meditations', reflecting on stoicism versus living fully. He decides to apply for a readership, watches a Four Corners documentary on the National Front, and the academic year's assessment winds down.", "1979-02": "Experiments resume — conjugated trypsin penetratograms on rat liver nuclei and boar sperm heads. Don Dunstan resigns as SA Premier and the China–Vietnam conflict dominates the news. Leigh reads Bronowski's essays, organises a biology summer school, and barbecues at Mylor with Bill Elliot and Ken Burton.", "1979-03": "The house extension begins ($20,000+ with a loan). Leigh hears visiting speakers Gunther Stent and George Brownlee, re-reads Gore Vidal's 'Julian', and gives a public talk on modern biology to 200 people at Salisbury CAE.", "1979-04": "Leigh hosts John B. Gurdon (FRS) from Cambridge at Flinders, discussing nucleocytoplasmic relations and chromatin over lunch at the staff club with Keith Dixon and Ted Martin. Easter Monday brings a family trip to Victor Harbour where Mark and Laura catch Tommy Ruffs and spot nesting penguins on Granite Island. Reflections on the Gracchi, truck driver blockades, and the swing from leftism to rightism.", "1979-05": "Thatcher wins the British election. Leigh hears Arthur Kornberg on the grant system, hosts Hans Zachau for chromatin discussions, and attends the Biochemistry Society meeting in Canberra. He reads E.O. Wilson's 'On Human Nature' and the house extension nears completion.", "1979-06": "A persistent cough plagues lecturing. Family life includes campfires, model rockets, and visits to sister Susan's new baby. Leigh reads 'The Salisbury Affair' by Stewart Cockburn, has a minor car accident at Morphetvale, reflects on the Vietnamese refugee crisis, and grinds through grant applications.", "1979-07": "Cold winter, grant writing (NIH application), and widespread household illness. The family awaits Skylab's re-entry. Leigh lunches with ex-Vietnam veterans, reads Blainey's 'The Tyranny of Distance', and has another car accident leading him to try the bus. Laura celebrates her birthday with a campfire.", "1979-08": "The family settles into the completed house extension. Leigh submits ARGC and NIH grant applications, attends a Medical Sciences Club debate on nuclear power, makes gunpowder for Mark, and sees The Mikado. On the farm, Mark is overjoyed at driving the new utility.", "1979-09": "Leigh marks exams at the Watson farm by an open fire among old eucalypts. He attends an Adelaide Cancer Research Group meeting on 'Neodifferentiation and miscreant membranes' by John Sabine, and notes the death of colleague Leonie Ashman's husband Ken from a brain tumour.", "1979-10": "Reflections on the Vietnamese refugee death toll and the SA state election ending the Labor era. Leigh's 40th birthday dinner with close friends. He dines with newly elected Premier David Tonkin at the Wheldrakes'. The October holiday is spent cutting down a candle-bark gum while Laura builds cubby houses, planting 'Super Marmande' tomatoes, and visiting the Northfield Pig Research Farm. By mid-October, Leigh is 'tired — tired — tired' of excessive assessment."}}};
